Show HN: Improve essay writing skills with ChatGPT
text:
Hey there folks, today I want to share with you how I came up with a ChatGPT-based service to improve essay writing skills, particularly for tests like PTE (Person Test of English) and IELTS.

Now, let me just say upfront that I'm not a huge fan of writing essays. But I know that practice makes perfect, so I force myself to write them every day in the hopes that they'll eventually become easier. However, one of the biggest challenges I face is that I don't always get immediate feedback on my writing. I have a weekly call with my English teacher, which is great, but it means that I have to wait to get feedback on my mistakes. And in the meantime, I keep making the same errors over and over again, which can be frustrating and slow down my progress.

That's where ChatGPT comes in. After some experimentation with prompt engineering, I discovered the one that allows me to get instant feedback on my writing. The AI checks things like structure, complexity, vocabulary, and so on, meaning that the main problem was solved.

But that's not all. I also realized that ChatGPT could help me take my writing skills to the next level. One day, I was curious to know how a native English speaker would express my thoughts. How close was I to perfect English writing? So I fed my essay into ChatGPT, explained how the perfect essay should be written, asked it to rewrite it as a native speaker would, and saved the meaning at the same time. And let me tell you, I was blown away by the level of English that ChatGPT produced.

I put these 2 features (personalized feedback and rewritten essay) into the website and now I am asking for your feedback. There is no need to sign up, just put an essay, and press the button.

Tell HN: Access to AWS and Amazon.com is now independent
text:
Was ecstatic to see this email from AWS. TLDR: AWS root logins used to be irreversibly tied to Amazon.com retail accounts (same password).

I made a huge fuss with AWS 5 years ago to make it possible to separate retail and AWS accounts, and they finally did it.

Huge pain point solved for founders who started companies signing up for AWS using their retail account, and later need to separate the root account (until this week, it wasn’t possible)

Sharing the email since I can’t find an official announcement.

—

Greetings from Amazon Web Services,

In the past, you have used the same email address and password to sign in to Amazon.com and AWS. In response to customer feedback, AWS is updating your account to make your access to Amazon.com and AWS independent. You can continue using this email address and your current password to sign in to Amazon.com. However, the next time that you sign in to AWS, you will be prompted to create a new password and will have the option to register a new multi-factor authentication (MFA) device. MFA is a best practice that adds an extra layer of protection on top of your email and password.

AWS will never email you and ask you to disclose your password. You will see the prompts to create a new password and register a new MFA device only when you visit the AWS Console at https://console.aws.amazon.com which will direct you to our secure sign-in experience hosted on the signin.aws subdomain.

This update to your AWS account also gives you the option to secure your AWS sign-in with additional MFA device types such as hardware security keys [1]. In addition, this update can help you monitor root user activity with AWS CloudTrail at no additional cost [2].

[1] To learn more about the types of MFA supported on AWS, visit our AWS IAM MFA User Guide: https://docs.aws.amazon.com/IAM/latest/UserGuide/id_credentials_mfa.html

[2] To learn more about about monitoring sign-in events to the Console, visit our AWS CloudTrail User Guide: https://docs.aws.amazon.com/awscloudtrail/latest/userguide/cloudtrail-event-reference-aws-console-sign-in-events.html

Chatr Data Breach
text:
I just received this email from Chatr Mobile (formerly Mobilicity; acquired by Rogers), an MVNO in Canada:

---

Subject: Important Information About Your Former Chatr Account

Dear Former chatr customer,

We take the privacy of your information very seriously and work hard to protect your information. Chatr is required to temporarily retain some information about former customer accounts after deactivation, including for tax purposes.

Through proactive monitoring, we identified some basic account details from your former account were posted online on January 12, 2023. We have not detected any unauthorized activity on your account and your account remains secure. As soon as we identified the issue, we took immediate action to protect your information and put additional safety measures in place.

We value the trust you place in us, and we sincerely apologize.

After completing a detailed analysis, we have determined that no financial information, date-of-birth, passwords, social insurance numbers or secret questions associated with your former account were posted or viewed. The basic account details accessed included: name, billing address, username, and email address used to activate this account, and if provided, account PIN, account contact telephone number and alternative contact telephone number.

As a precaution we encourage you to regularly update secret questions, use strong passwords, avoid using the same passwords, and keep passwords safely stored. Also, beware of phishing attempts and never click on links sent in text messages or emails unless you are expecting them or they’re from trusted sources.

As a reminder, we will never call, email, or text you and ask for your password, secret questions/answers or account PIN.

If you have questions, please contact chatr customer care at 1-800-485-9745.

Sincerely,

Cameron McFadyen, General Manager, chatr
